For the sake of documentation: 

It feels like a long season of loss. I wake up each morning on the hunt for the wins - past, present, and future. I know they are there even though they feel elusive. 

I refer to it as Covid Clarity. You know. The kind of revelations you only get when you lay in bed for 7 days, experiencing invisible tremors, eyes closed between meals, and games of Battleship with your quarantine companion. 

I speak to her, through a mask, with a relaxed confidence, and walk out the door knowing the cards are in my hand, certain that whatever change is coming will be of my own doing. 

I work and rework the words to shape them into something that will feel more fulfilling. The problem is that all of who I am is uncontainable. There is no box into which I am willing to fit. 

I stare at the four faces on the screen; some I know though they don’t know me. I tell them I’ve learned that I can do anything. Anything. I don’t think they believe me. 

I remind them that these results are not a reflection of their capabilities. That this is just a set of circumstances through which we must play. Suffering is temporary. 

“Do not allow my confidence to offend your insecurities.” - @deionsanders 

#wherethelightis #thesacrednessoflight #selfportrait #seeingself #morningslikethese #powerofpresence #randomthoughts #livemoremagic #believe

You wake up at 1:34 a.m. and know immediately that there is no chance of going back to sleep. But you take more melatonin and slide yourself under the weighted blanket anyway. You think of all that transpired the day before. Remind yourself that even if you did make a mistake, there is nothing left for you to do now but wait. Just wait. 

You carry in wood from outside and build yourself a fire. It is just you and the reflection of lights from the tree and the heat of the flames at 3:37 a.m.

The questions he asked resurface: Has it gotten better? No. Will you stay? No. Are you looking? Yes. That’s good, he says. Not that you need validation from the stranger trying to piece together the fragments of your life into something recognizable. Something definable.

The cards never lie: 

• Be tenacious in the pursuit of your desires.
• Create! Create! Create!
• Be vulnerable with your truth.
• Know your Self.
• Stay open-hearted.

Drink your water. Drink your nettles. Put on your winter whites. Step into your life.

This is my second year coaching at the high school level, and it has been during what I would consider to be one of the more difficult stretches of life stuff I have experienced in quite some time. 

For as challenging as this season has been, it has also been so incredibly rewarding. It is a welcomed distraction that fills me with purpose, and it has helped me to remember that my value is not in my work but in how I build relationships with others. They challenge and teach me as much as I try to challenge and teach them. 

Eleven games left. Eleven more chances to break some records. Eleven more chances to make more memories. Eleven more chances to make some history.

This is us after winning our first league game in 9 years. Nine!

“You look refreshed,” she says. You say something about having four days in a row of no work - that is why. “No,” he says. “It was not the time off. It was the people. It was you doing the work you love to do.” 

You have been drowning in the Rio Aboja Rio, your third eye begging to open, your soul struggling against the weight of the water, desperate for the light that skims the surface.

But it was those days - not the four days of rest, but the four days before. Those four days before, with those humans and their stories and their desires and their vulnerabilities and their intelligences and their earnestness and their insecurities and their bravery and their gratitudes. 

Those four days with those humans reminded you of your own need to serve and be served. Of your need to be curious and kind and engaged. Of your need to be a dreamer of big dreams.

And it almost feels silly to say out loud that in only four days you can change your life, except you know that you are living its proof. Just look at how refreshed you are!

There are these moments in life where you know nothing will ever be the same - that YOU will never be the same.

“Your gut won’t lie to you.” - @migueld1 via @kylebilllings

I remember sitting in this room in November 2020, still numb and a ghost of myself post-fire evacuation. I would sit at my desk with @brooklynwriterscollective and try to write, but mostly I just listened. I listened and stared out the windows at the scarred earth and gray skies, and I was cold, so cold. (These large single-pane windows let in all the beauty, but they also let in all the cold.) And yet those mornings at my desk by the windows with the cold air circling my ankles were also life-giving moments. 

I've been asked to dream my wildest dreams, and I am trying my very darndest to do so. I miss writing. I miss writing in community. I miss creating in community. I'm just going to start throwing some things out here in case my wildest dreams might also be your wildest dreams. 

Happy Holy Tuesday.

In the spring of 2021, I walked out of that school building, vowing to haunt her for the rest of her days. 

In the winter of 2021, a collection of individuals found me, and we shared story after story after story and found the throughline. It is amazing what a lack of leadership can do to a network that should be designed to support expansion.

And so we stayed up night after night reading board policies, finding the right words and the right times to tell all of the truth, to make our desires heard - not just for me and mine, but for theirs and theirs.

(I sometimes think people in this town are only friendly to me because they are afraid I will speak their name into a microphone. But I only do what needs to be done out of love. And sometimes justice.)

And so today, this is the face of a mother who feels like the collective slayed the dragon. This was the last meeting we will ever have where we have to document the lies and endure the constant gaslighting by someone who is supposed to be the expression of what we hope our children can become. 

We made it. She is gone. She is gone. And my haunting days are over.

#wherethelightis #motherhood #blackmothers #truthtelling #thesacrednessoftruth #stamina #dotherightthing

“What is it that you think you’re entitled to?”

The question continues to reverberate in my mind, in my body. Because you see, it was not a question asked in such a way as to invite me into expansion, but as a way of cutting away at me, to remind me that I shouldn’t be so bold as to ask for what I want or deserve. As in, Who do You think You are?

Over the long weekend, I read @tarasophiamohr’s book Playing Big. This quote, in particular, illuminated the dynamics at play that I continue to bump against: 

“Research shows that women incur social costs for advocating for themselves too strongly; they are seen as less likable by those around them, especially by other women.”

So thank you to the ones who push ego aside; who speak truth boldly; who can say “I’m sorry” and “How can I help?”; who will hold your hand in the dark; who will wipe your tears; who will build a tent; who will speak your name in rooms when you aren’t there; who will pour you a glass of wine and feed you castrelvetanos on a park bench; who will walk with you for miles and miles.

Thank goodness for those women. You know who you are. 

#gratitude #morningslikethese #thesacrednessoflight #coffeetime #womensupportingwomen #lovelovelove #truthtelling #playingbig

She asked me if I would consider writing a poem for this issue. It’s something we’ve never done before, she says. I agree to take on the challenge. After all, I do miss words - I miss the weaving of words into something meaningful and vulnerable, and true. The words come to me quickly on a rainy afternoon in February. She says the theme of the poem is serendipitous. The title of the issue references the sky. There are no such things as accidents. 

For me, this poem is part remembrance and part prophecy. It is a reminder of how far we have come and how much more still awaits, and how the universe is always conspiring in your favor.

Thank you @conniffcate for seeing me and giving me the opportunity to contribute. And thank you @napavintners for allowing us the freedom to experiment.

But you are indeed hungry. Starving. Ravenous. Insatiable. Unfilled. Yearning. 

But you are not chasing. You are in passionate pursuit of purpose and meaning and beauty and laughter and pleasure and ecstasy and enchantment.

“It all comes down to this: You chase what you want, and you don’t take what you can get.”

You sit across from one another, making eye contact through the screen. She tells you that your time here is not yet done. It is not what you want to hear. What you want her to say to you is that it is okay for you to walk away with the rest of them. 

But deep down, you know she is right. This is not the right time in your life to take this kind of risk. And besides… You are being intentionally discriminating. What you want is so specific and so not yet in existence. 

What you want feels like a fever dream, but it was your dreaming that got you all the way here. It was your dreaming that got you all the way here. It was your dreaming that got you all the way here. 

It was your dreaming that got you all the way here.

“It was like two weeks in one,” I say, my voice is still raspy from the baseball and basketball games. I head home for the weekend, leave the computer in the office; I don’t want to be tempted. 

I stare at the piles of things and the books that are misplaced and realize that this anxiety about the disorder is really about me feeling out of control. 

I could say that there is nothing special in this glass. But I am drinking it as I stare at the golden hillside and as scrub jays fly in front of my face and squirrels scurry below. I am drinking it as I think about the clear blue sky above me, and I think about the old redwoods above and as I think about embracing surrender.

“Safe travels” was the last thing I said. The days pass, and I try not to think about the time passing between each text. They tell me they are praying. I try to formulate prayers of my own. 

I’ve learned that prayer does not require you to be on your knees. And so that means you can pray at your standing desk. You can pray at the water station and while you brush your teeth and while you talk about fantasy football and while they ask you questions about backend systems. 

I don’t think there is a separation between your spiritual body and your physical body; I believe we inhabit both at the same time. Every wave of a hand is a prayer. Every step is a prayer. Every blink of an eye, every inhale, and every exhale. A life is a prayer.

Year 1 of the 5-year plan, only two weeks into the season, and I am so proud of us already. 

Yesterday, we spent two hours in the gym, getting to know ourselves and one another. These 14-17-year-olds told ME what they wanted and needed. (Turns out all you have to do is ask.) Though I might be their coach, this is, ultimately, their team, their memories, their successes. 

My role is to support them by giving them permission to dream and decide and then do my best to provide them with the tools they need to succeed.

(Sometimes I think teenagers get a bad rap, but I can tell you, based on at least my very small sample size, that the kids are alright.)

Yesterday let me be who I truly am and clarified for me the need to escape the places where I am forced to play small. I want for me what I want for them—confidence, courage, freedom. 

#gratitudes #hoopdreams #morningslikethese #thesacrednessoflight #saints #lovemyteam #morethanagame

I was going to call it a Caremare — the kind of dream you have that leaves you anxious out of a genuine desire to protect and serve. But in reality, it was indeed a nightmare, a bad dream, induced by the fear of doing the wrong thing, disappointing someone outside of my self. 

It took ninety-something minutes of laying in the dark to crawl my way closer to the light of truth: You can both care deeply and also screw things up. You can exhaust yourself in honest pursuit and still make a million mistakes. You can love and hurt. And that's just being human. 

“Progress over perfection,” I repeat to them. Honest effort and intentional action over just going through the motions. Because, at least then, we are learning something.

My latest for @magnolia. In all honesty, I struggled with this particular assignment. I was distracted by my self-absorption. No, not absorption. It was because I had been in a long stretch of feeling disconnected - from self, from work, from life - and as I conducted interview after interview, I was gifted old memories and meaning that reminded me of how much I am fed by authentic relationships.

My time with all of the interviewees also reminded me of the power of story. Through story, when we can see ourselves, then we can see another’s humanity, hopefully deepen our compassion, view the world with more love and understanding.

Hello Insta-friends, Napa-Valley-friends, Chicago-friends, businesses, and families.

I’ve been quiet here because I'm deep in basketball season, working year one of my 5-year plan for the girls' basketball program while also working full-time and supporting my own family of 5. But I’m hopping on today to make a small-to-big request that's outside of the food/wine/hospitality space that I also love. 

I’m very proud and feel very fortunate to coach the St. Helena Girls’ basketball team, and we are currently fundraising for equipment bags and warm-ups. Our program goal is $5000. Anything over that will help me fund our summer league and the @gaelswbb summer basketball camp that I hope to have some of our players attend. 

I know it’s the holiday season, and you’ve probably done a lot of donating over the past year, but any support you’re able to offer, even if it means just spreading the word, would be great. I’m working to give them what I had when I was a player their age, which is the least I can do!

Visit the @sthelenagirlsbasketball profile or leave a message here, and I’ll send you the letter and answer any questions you might have. 

Thank you in advance, always. ❤️🏀❤️

#womeninsports #sthelenagirlsbasketball #shhsgirlsbasketball #womensupportingwomen

At the game, we watch one of the boys prepare to shoot a free throw. She looks back at me and says, “Remember how Pratt used to lick her hands and wipe the bottom of her shoes each time?” We laugh. “I don’t know where she is now,” I say. 

On the car ride home, I Google her name and find an obituary from 2022. At first, I think I’m mistaken. But I recognize the smile and her nose, even though her hair is much shorter and her face is a little more round. I click through and read the short paragraphs about who she became and the people she left behind, of which there are many, as it should be when you die at 36. 

There is a line that tells me what I want to know most: Nicole was a basketball coach…

I’ve been thinking about her a lot over the last few days. About the nights she slept over at my house. About our matching game-day socks. About her fiery temper and her childlike sweetness. About how different our lives were, and yet we both ended up in the same place: back on the basketball court.
